[4] USA (Ohio)
Date: Fri 18 Jul 2014
Source: The Columbus Dispatch [abridged, edited]
http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2014/07/17/Measles-outbreak-might-be-over.html


The end of Ohio's measles outbreak could be in sight; the last confirmed case was reported nearly 3 weeks ago. At the same time, the mumps outbreak in central Ohio continues to infect people.

The highly contagious measles virus has an incubation period that can last 21 days, and the last confirmed case was reported on 30 Jun 2014 in Holmes County. That means the outbreak could unofficially be over by 21 Jul 2014, said Brian Fowler, chief of vaccine-preventable-disease epidemiology at the Ohio Department of Health. However, the state won't consider the outbreak officially over until 2 incubation periods, or 42 consecutive days, have passed. That would make the official end date 11 Aug 2014 if no additional cases are confirmed.

Measles symptoms usually appear 7 to 21 days after exposure and include a fever followed by a cough, a runny nose and a red, blotchy rash on the face that spreads down the neck and body over several days. The disease is most contagious 4 days before and 4 days after the rash appears and can be deadly for babies and young children.

Measles cases are at a 20-year high in the United States, driven largely by the outbreak among unvaccinated Amish populations in Ohio. The outbreak's spread has leveled off at 368 reported cases with 10 hospitalizations in 9 counties: Ashland, Coshocton, Crawford, Highland, Holmes, Knox, Richland, Stark and Wayne. Knox County, where more than half of the cases have been reported, hasn't had a confirmed case since 11 Jun 2014. That makes the county's official end date 23 Jul 2014, said Pam Palm, spokeswoman for the health department there. The county, which has had 195 cases and 5 hospitalizations in its largely Amish population, has administered 1518 doses of the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine since the outbreak started. "We were able to immunize about 30 or 40 percent of the Amish in the community and probably more in the Danville area where the majority of the people that had the measles were located," Palm said.

[Byline: Dominic Binkley]

