[5] Russia (Tyumen)
Date: Mon 14 Jul 2014
Source: Nash Gorod.ru [in Russian, machine trans. abridged, edited]
http://www.nashgorod.ru/news/news66991.html


The number of measles cases in the Tyumen Region [Oblast] has increased over the last week and affected 47 people. They comprise 17 adults, including 4 older than 35, and 30 children. 4 of them children are under one year, and 16 children are aged from one year to 16 years. According to the Regional Centre for Surveillance of Measles (Novosibirsk), 39 are laboratory confirmed cases, and material from 3 patients is being genotyped by the National Centre for Surveillance of measles in Moscow. 4 patients are receiving treatment in an Infectious Diseases Hospital.

Measles is severe acute infectious viral disease and highly contagious. Measles is contracted via upper respiratory mucosa and conjunctiva, so runny nose, conjunctivitis, laryngitis, bronchitis, and pneumonia are common manifestations of measles, as well as the characteristic rash. Transmission is carried by droplets, a few days before the rash appears. At risk are persons without a history of measles and those who are inadequately immunised against measles. Such people are highly susceptible to measles throughout life and can develop it at any age.

The most effective and affordable way to prevent disease is vaccination. Routine immunization against measles has been held throughout Russia, including in the Tyumen Region, annually since 1968. Free vaccination against measles is provided by organizations of the state and municipal health care system in the community and workplace.

