[10] Australia (Victoria)
Date: Thu 17 Jul 2014
Source: ABC TV News [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-17/measles-cases-in-victoria-hit-15-year-high/5604628


The number of measles cases in Victoria has hit a 15-year high, prompting an alert to general practitioners and hospital emergency departments. The health department says 57 people have been diagnosed with the highly infectious airborne illness since the start of the year [2014]. 16 new cases have been reported since 1 May 2014. Several children were so ill that they needed hospital treatment.

Two Melbourne health care workers have also been diagnosed with measles this week, and people who have returned from overseas travel have also been affected. "The last 2 years were quite low. In the equivalent time period, we had 6 reported last year [2013] and 11 reported in 2012," Chief Health Officer Dr Rosemary Lester said.

Hospital emergency departments and GPs have been advised to look out for symptoms, which include a rash, fever, severe cough and conjunctivitis. Dr Lester says "good immunisation coverage in our younger people" had helped control the spread of the illness. "It's very important that children be immunised on time," she said. Also, people who have a compromised immune system are at risk.

